title: Fire ruins south from 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St., 1889
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Ruins. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. Looking South from Washington Street." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Right side: Harrington & Smith, ship chandlers, etc. Dexter Horton Bank."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: Guy Phinney house, 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Houses. Phinney, Guy. House at Broadway and James Street 1889."

title: View east from Madison St. and Western Ave., 1895
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Madison Street 1895. Looking East from Western Avenue. 1. Rainier Club. 2. Providence Hospital. 3. Cordray Theater. 4. Central School 5. Rainier Hotel. 6. Chamber of Commerce (M. V. B. Stacy home)."

title: Holy Names Academy at 7th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St., ca. 1898
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Schools. Academy of the Holy Names. Ninth Avenue and Jackson Street. Built 1883, demolished about 1907. 1898? Beacon Hill in background. Adam Orth house left of center. Paulson's Row at center." The location provided in the caption is incorrect. The school was located at 7th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St.
intersection: 7th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St.

title: First logs on Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad, 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Transportation. Columbia and Puget Sound railroad. First load of logs. 1880. 1. Academy of the Holy Names. 2. Beacon Hill."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. King St.

title: Yesler's wharf, 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Wharves. Yesler's wharf. Foot of Mill Street [Yesler Way]. 1880. 1. Crawford and Harrington's wharf. 2. Dakota (Steamer). San Francisco-Seattle run 1876, excursions to Alaska after 1882. 3. J. B. Libby, built 1863 in Seattle, wrecked in Strait of Juan de Fuca, 1889."

title: View from 2nd Ave. and Pike St., 1878.
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Second Avenue and Pike Street 1878. Looking southeast. 1. A.W. Piper house. 2. I.N Bigelow house. 3. John Denny house. 4. Densmore house. 5. J. D. Jordan house. 6. J. F. T. Mitchel house. 6. Rev. Whitworth house. 8. Territorial University."

title: Princess Angeline, 1893
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Portraits. Angeline, Princess." Caption on image: "Angeline, daughter of Chief Seattle. Copyright, 1893, by J. P. Soule,  lower center."

title: Stetson and Post Mill at waterfront between S. King St. and S. Weller St., 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Mills. Stetson and Post mill. 1882. Located at Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] at King and Weller. Completed 1882, burned 1889."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. King St.

title: Temporary buildings at 2nd Ave. and James St. following fire, ca. June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Reconstruction. Temporary buildings. Second Avenue at James Street."

title: View from near 3rd Ave. and Pine St., 1890
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Denny Hill, 1890. Looking South. 1. First Methodist Protestant Church. Built 1889-1890, demolished 1907. 2. Abbott House. 3. Armory. 4. Young Naturalist building. 5. University. 6. Providence Hospital. 7. Central School."

title: Temporary tents  at 2nd Ave. and Marion St. following fire, June 1889
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Reconstruction.  Second Avenue. Looking northwest from Marion Street." Transcribed from back of photograph: " Stairway to Stetson and Post Row, Second and Marion Street. Caption on image: Number 18,  lower left."
subjects: Lake Union Furniture Manufacturing Company (Seattle, Wash.)

title: View south on 1st Ave. S. from Yesler Way, 1885
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1885. Looking South from Mill Street [Yesler Way]." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Marshall Block large Building to Right. Dexter Horton to right of Marshall's, Harrington and Smith adjoining, Sam Kenny's tailor shop next and Keith's barber shop adjoining. Left--Kelly's drugstore, Smith's butcher shop, Saddle Rock restaurant, John Sullivan's notions store. Domed roof Squire's Opera House."

title: View from 2nd Ave. and Virginia St., 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Second Avenue and Virginia Street. 1882. Belltown hill, looking North. Houses--1. Case. 2. Coombs. 3. Nation. 4. Ingraham. 5. Cooper. 6. Comption. 7. Lobe. 8. Reynolds."

title: Kellogg's Drugstore and Pinkham's Variety Store at 1st Ave. and Yesler Way, 1885
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Buildings. Kellogg's drugstore and Pinkham's variety store. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] and Mill Street [Yesler Way]. Built 1865. 1865. E. M. Sammis photograph gallery on second floor."

title: View north from 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St., 1865
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1865. Looking North, just below Washington Street intersection. Center Right side: Occidental Hotel (with flagstaff). Above that--Dr. H. A. Smith house. Above that--C.C. Terry house (white fence and gables). Below right of Terry house--J. Collins house. Left of hotel. Left side: Hillory Butler house.(small white). Center Right side: first Masonic Hall (dark building). Above that -- Methodist Episcopal Church (White Church)."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: 2nd Ave. looking north from Yesler Way, 1913
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Second Avenue 1913. Looking North from Yesler Way. 1. L. C. Smith building under construction. 2. Seattle Hotel. 3. Hoge Building." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Right side:  Smith Building. Collins Block. Alaska Block.  Left side: Yesler Block. Seattle Hotel. Butler Hotel. Bailey Building (Railway Exchange). Hoge Building."

title: Pier No. 5, 1913
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Wharves. Pier No. 5. 1913. Ships--1. Humboldt (Steamer). 2. Ohio (Steamer)."

title: Reconstruction at 2nd Ave. and Spring St. following fire, June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Reconstruction. Second Avenue. Looking North from Spring Street."
subjects: Avery, Kirk and Lansing Company (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Ruins of Main St. wharves following fire, ca. June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Ruins. Wharves at foot of Main Street."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. Washington St.

title: View south from Denny Hill, 1891
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Denny Hill. 1891. Looking southwest. 1. Second Avenue. 2. First Avenue. 3. Bay Building."

title: View from 4th Ave. and Seneca St., 1870
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Views. From Fourth Avenue and Seneca Street. 1870. Looking southeast. 1. Morley house. 2. Public school. 3. Yesler's dock and mill. 4. 'Brown Church' (First Methodist Protestant church)." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Right side: Steeple 'Brown Church'. M. P. Yesler's dock and Yesler's mill. Center Right side:  Public school--well on playground. Amasa Miller home to left of school. Left foreground--Morley house."

title: View north from 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., ca. 1864
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street. About 1864. Looking North from Main Street." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Left side: Tremont House. McAleer's, stoves and tin ware. Right side: Pinkham's store."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Temporary buildings at 3rd Ave. and James St. following fire, ca. June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Reconstruction. Temporary buildings on Third Avenue between James Street and Jefferson Street. 1889. Yesler house at left background, King County Courthouse at right background."

title: Oregon Improvement Company wharf, ca. 1890
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Wharves.  Jackson and Washington Street."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. Washington St.

title: Yesler's Cook House, 1860
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Buildings. Yesler's cook house. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] between Mill Street [Yesler Way] and Washington Street. Built 1852, demolished 1866. 1860. First public building in Seattle proper. Fifteen feet square. Built by Dr. Maynard."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: View from Beacon Hill, ca. 1881
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Beacon Hill. 1881. Looking northeast. E.S. Turner house. Center foreground. Columbia-Puget Sound Railroad bridge, center. First Seattle Gas Works. (Seattle Gaslight Co.) right of bridge in cove." The same photograph appears in the University of Washington's Prosch Seattle Album, Volume 2, page 28 with the following caption: "Seattle in 1882, from Dearborn Street and Twelfth Avenue South, looking N.W. Among buildings are Stetson & Post sawmill, gas works, County Courthouse, Catholic, Episcopal and Methodist Churches, Squire's Opera House, Frauenthal and Post buildings, Yesler Wharf."
intersection: 12th Ave. S. and S. Dearborn St.

title: Intelligencer Office near 1st Ave. and Cherry St., ca. 1876
description: Constructed by Henry Yesler in 1874, this building served as an office for the Seattle Intelligencer Newspaper (which would later evolve into the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.)

title: Central School, ca. 1887
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Schools. Central School. Sixth Avenue and Madison Street. Built 1883, destroyed by fire, 1888. Exterior. Frame. Front view. 1887." View from approximately 4th Ave. and Marion St.

title: View south from 5th Ave. and Pine St., 1887
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Fifth Avenue and Pine Street. Looking South. 1887. 1. Coppin's water works. 2. Sixth Street School. 3. Providence hospital. 4. Territorial University."

title: Occidental Hotel  ruins following fire, June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. Ruins. Occidental Hotel. Front [1st Ave.] Street and James Street. West facade."

title: View SW from 32nd Ave., 1898
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Thirty-second Avenue. South. 1898."

title: Arlington Hotel at 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., ca. 1883
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Hotels. Arlington House. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] and Main Street. Built 1876, destroyed by fire June 6, 1889. 1883? 1.  Jake Levy." The same photograph appears in the University of Washington digital collections where it is noted the building is decorated for the visit of North Pacific Railroad president, Henry Villard.
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: View NE from 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] 1880. Looking northeast from Main Street. 1. A. P. Hotaling, liquor store. 2. Stowell drug store. 3. Hotel Brunswick and Squire's Opera House." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Hotel Brunswick and Squire's Opera House. McNaught, Mitchel and McNaught law office next. (Toklas and Singerman below). A. P. Hotaling liquor store."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Native American camp on Ballast Island, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfront. 1880-1889. Indian camp on ballast dump at foot of Washington Street."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. Washington St.

title: View north from 1st Ave. and Cherry, 1870
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Front Street [1st Ave.]. 1870. Looking North from Cherry Street. 1. Intelligencer building. 2. L. A. Treen shoe store. 3. S. L. Benjamin book store." Transcribed from back of photo: "F. W. Wald, hardware. Reinig store (agent for Singer sewing machines). Over Reinig's, Puget Sound Business College. Left side: Intelligencer building.  Treen & Co. shoe store. S.L. Benjamin book store."

title: View of Seattle south from Denny Hill, 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Denny Hill. 1882. Looking South."

title: Occidental Hotel at 1st Ave. and James St., 1872
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Hotels. Occidental Hotel. Front Street [1st Ave.] and James Street. Built 1865; demolished about 1883. As seen from Occidental Ave. and Main St. 1872. 1. Mrs. Francis Guy's boarding house 2. Occidental hotel 3. A. Slorah's saloon."

title: View from 2nd Ave. and Pike St., 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Second Avenue and Pike Street. 1870 Looking southeast. 1. Territorial University. 2. Andrew W. Piper house."

title: View north from Pine St., 1885
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Pine St. Vicinity. About 1885. Looking North to Lake Union."

title: Yesler Way, west from 1st Ave., 1875
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Mill Street. 1875. Looking West from Front Street. 1. Yesler's mill. 2. News and Book depot. 3. City market. 4. Matthew A. Kelly's Pioneer Drug Store. 5. Seattle Bakery."

title: Plummer's Store, 1860
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Buildings. Plummer's store. Southwest corner of Commercial Street and Main Street. Built 1858-1859; destroyed by fire June 6, 1889. 1860. Second floor known as Snoqualmie Hall used for court sessions, dances and social affairs. Later Tremont Hotel. Plummer's dock in background."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and Main St. S.

title: Occidental Hotel, 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Hotels. Occidental Hotel. Front Street and James Street. Built 1865; demolished about 1883. 1870. 1. Hillory Butler house. 2. Henry A. Atkins house. 3.  J. M. Coleman house."

title: John J. McGilvra House, 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Houses. McGilvra, John J. Exterior. Laurel Shade Road. Built 1864, destroyed by fire 1933. 1870." Laurel Shade Road can be seen in the 1905 and 1912 Baist Atlases. It runs along the present-day path of 43rd Ave. E.

title: View south from 2nd Ave. and Pike Street, 1878
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Views. From 2nd Ave. and Pike St. 1878. Looking south. 1. John Jordan house (2nd & Pike) 2. Grandma Denny house (3rd & Union) present post office site 3. J.F.T. Mitchell house (next to above) Dexter Horton House (3rd & Seneca?) 5. A.A. Denny house (1st & Union)." Transcribed from back of photo: "Pikes Street. Second Street. Third Street. Union Street. Peiser copy.  94x W & S." L. John Jordan home 3d St. left to right: Grandma Denny's home, Harmon house and shop, J.F.T. Mitchell home, Dexter Horton home, Guye home. See Bagley for clearer print. (This note refers to Clarence Bagley's 'History of King County' published by The S. J. Clarke Publishing Company in 1929, page 251 which features a cropped view of photograph)."

title: 1st Ave. S. north from S. Main St.,  1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1880. Looking North from Main Street. 1. New England house. 2. Z. C. Miles store. 3. Squire's Opera House and Hotel Brunswick." Transcribed from back of photograph: "On verso:  Commercial Street. Right side: Brunswick Hotel and Squire's Opera House. Pinkham's clothing store. Frauenthal Block. Z. C. Miles. Left side: New England Hotel. First person to right is John Burns."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and Main St. S.

title: Territorial University, 1864
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Colleges and Universities. Washington (State) University. Territorial University. Main building exterior. Fourth Avenue and University Street. Built 1861-1862. Demolished 1910 (the columns are now in the Sylvan Theater, University campus) 1864. Photo by Webster & Stevens. John Pike, architect."

title: View north from 1st Ave. and Cherry St., ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street [1st Ave.] about 1880. Looking North from Cherry Street. 1. L. S. Rowe, grocer. 2. L. A. Treen, shoes. 3. Fountain Beer Hall. 4. Evans butcher shop.  R-Evans butcher shop. Hendricks plumbing. F.W. Wald, hardware. Reinig Block. Elephant store. Maddock's block in distance. L-L. S. Rowe, groceries. L. A. Treen, shoes. Fountain Beer Hall. Occidental Brotherhood building. S. Baxter and Co."

title: Temporary tents erected after fire near 2nd Ave. and Columbia St., July 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, Reconstruction. Second Avenue. Looking northeast from Columbia Street. July 1889."

title: Coal Bunkers of Oregon Improvement Co., ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfront. Coal bunkers of the Oregon Improvement Company. King Street. Captain John Williamson in foreground."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. King St.
